docs.abstract: Zach Stafford, the former editor in chief of The Advocate, traveled to gay safe havens as he has for so many summers, but the summer of 2020 was different.
docs.snippet: Zach Stafford, the former editor in chief of The Advocate, traveled to gay safe havens as he has for so many summers, but the summer of 2020 was different.
docs.lead_paragraph: Just days after the pandemic made landfall in New York City in the spring of 2020 — and right as the city streets became ghostly reminders of what was — I began to run every morning.

headline.main: A Black Man Ran to Gay Enclaves to Feel Safe. But Was He Welcome?
headline.print_headline: Feeling Unwelcome at a Gay Haven

docs.abstract: Some Republicans have linked their criticism of President Biden’s Supreme Court nominee to the support she has received from Demand Justice, a group that wants to expand the court.
docs.snippet: Some Republicans have linked their criticism of President Biden’s Supreme Court nominee to the support she has received from Demand Justice, a group that wants to expand the court.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Hundreds of progressive activists crowded into the Hamilton music venue a few blocks from the White House on Monday night to celebrate the nomination of Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson, listen to queen of funk Chaka Khan perform and hear someone, as the song goes, tell them something good.

headline.main: Republicans Target Progressive Advocacy Group Amid Opposition to Jackson
headline.print_headline: Republicans Target Group That Supports Jackson

docs.abstract: Pamela Moses, who was sentenced in January to six years in a case that outraged voting rights supporters, will not face a new trial, a district attorney said.
docs.snippet: Pamela Moses, who was sentenced in January to six years in a case that outraged voting rights supporters, will not face a new trial, a district attorney said.
docs.lead_paragraph: A Tennessee prosecutor dropped all criminal charges on Friday against Pamela Moses, a Memphis woman with a previous felony conviction who was sentenced to six years and one day in prison in January after she tried to restore her right to vote in 2019.

headline.main: Charges Dropped Against Tennessee Woman Who Was Jailed Over Voter Fraud

docs.abstract: She was an artist who was studying anthropology when she became an activist in the civil rights movement and a rare woman to document Black life in photos.
docs.snippet: She was an artist who was studying anthropology when she became an activist in the civil rights movement and a rare woman to document Black life in photos.
docs.lead_paragraph: Doris Derby, an educator, artist, activist and civil rights era photographer who turned her camera away from the violence of the times to capture the quieter moments of the movement, and in so doing documented the transformation of Black life in rural Mississippi, died on March 28 in Atlanta. She was 82.

headline.main: Doris Derby, Civil Rights Era Photographer, Dies at 82
headline.print_headline: Doris Derby Dies at 82; Captured the Quiet Side Of the Civil Rights Era

docs.abstract: The platform just doesn’t matter as much as we seem to think it does.
docs.snippet: The platform just doesn’t matter as much as we seem to think it does.
docs.lead_paragraph: I started my Twitter account in June 2008. And after 14 years on the platform, I have a lot of feelings about it. Twitter is meaningful to me, while constantly leaving me wondering why, exactly, that is the case.

headline.main: Can We Please Get Over Our Twitter Obsession Already?

docs.abstract: The officer, Jason Van Dyke, had served about three years in state prison for murdering the Black teenager, a killing that put a spotlight on police brutality.
docs.snippet: The officer, Jason Van Dyke, had served about three years in state prison for murdering the Black teenager, a killing that put a spotlight on police brutality.
docs.lead_paragraph: Federal prosecutors said on Monday that they would not bring criminal charges against a former Chicago police officer who served about three years in state prison after being convicted of second-degree murder in the 2014 shooting of Laquan McDonald, a Black teenager.

headline.main: Ex-Chicago Officer Who Killed Laquan McDonald Won’t Face Federal Charges
